---
// Automation tiers — the section that disambiguates the three ways Pace
// repeats work, because the words "flow", "recipe", and "skill" get used
// interchangeably everywhere else and they are NOT the same thing:
//
//   Flows   — user-recorded Accessibility steps, replayed verbatim (pixel tier)
//   Recipes — pre-built flows Pace ships, installed by voice
//   Skills  — natural-language step lists the planner RE-GROUNDS each run
//             (intent tier); taught by voice or a typed form, structured
//             on-device by the privacy-pinned local planner
//
// Same shape as OnDevice/MeetingNotes: one claim, prose left, an
// illustrative artifact right. The artifact is a real-shaped .skill.md,
// because the honest proof of a taught skill is the plain-text file it
// becomes on disk. All claims verified against AGENTS.md.
---

<section id="automation" class="px-6 py-24 md:py-36 border-t border-[var(--color-border-subtle)]">
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
    <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-widest text-[var(--color-text-muted)] font-mono mb-6">
      Automation
    </p>

    <h2 class="pace-display text-4xl md:text-6xl text-white mb-12 max-w-3xl">
      Three ways to repeat work. <em>They're different on purpose.</em>
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 md:gap-16 items-start">
      <div class="pace-prose">
        <p>
          <strong>Flows</strong> are the literal tier. You record a sequence
          of clicks and keystrokes once; Pace replays them verbatim through
          the Accessibility tree. Same buttons, same order, every time —
          perfect when the layout never moves.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Recipes</strong> are flows Pace already ships. Say "install
          the morning standup recipe" and a pre-built sequence copies into
          your library, ready to run. No recording, no setup.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Skills</strong> are the flexible tier, and the part people
          conflate with the other two. A skill is a numbered list of steps in
          plain language — not recorded clicks. Pace <em>re-reads your screen
          and re-plans it every single run</em>, so a skill still works after
          a button moves or a menu gets renamed. Teach one by talking ("teach
          a skill that files my expense report") or by filling in a short
          form. The description is structured into a file by the on-device
          planner — the same local pin meeting notes use. A taught skill never
          leaves the Mac.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <p class="text-xs font-mono text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mb-3 uppercase tracking-wider">
          A taught skill on disk — illustrative
        </p>
        <div
          class="font-mono text-sm bg-black border border-[var(--color-border-subtle)] rounded-lg p-5 leading-relaxed"
        >
          <div class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">~/Library/…/Pace/skills/file-expense.skill.md</div>
          <div class="mt-3 text-white/80"># File an expense report</div>
          <div class="mt-2 text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">## Steps</div>
          <div class="text-white/70">1. Open the Expenses app</div>
          <div class="text-white/70">2. Start a new report for this month</div>
          <div class="text-white/70">3. Attach the latest receipt from Downloads</div>
          <div class="text-white/70">4. Submit it to Finance</div>
          <div class="mt-3 pt-3 border-t border-[var(--color-border-subtle)]">
            <span class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">you: </span>
            <span class="text-white">"run file expense"</span>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-1">
            <span class="text-[var(--color-positive)]">pace </span>
            <span class="text-white/80">re-reads the screen and re-plans each step. Not a macro — intent.</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="pace-margin-note mt-5">
          It's plain markdown. Open it, edit a step, delete it —<br />
          an ordinary file you own, structured on your Mac.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- The distinction, said plainly, so nobody leaves thinking a skill
         is just a recorded macro. -->
    <div class="mt-16 md:mt-20 pt-10 border-t border-[var(--color-border-subtle)] grid md:grid-cols-[1fr_14rem] gap-4 md:gap-10 items-start">
      <p class="pace-prose max-w-xl">
        The short version: <strong>flows replay pixels, skills replay
        intent.</strong> If the UI is frozen and you want the exact same
        motions, record a flow. If the UI drifts and you want the outcome
        regardless, teach a skill. Recipes are just the flows worth shipping
        in the box.
      </p>
      <p class="pace-margin-note md:border-l md:border-[var(--color-border-subtle)] md:pl-4">
        Five recipes ship today — standup, weekly review, email zero, focus
        mode, end-of-day shutdown.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
